hazard analysis system for slac personnel page 1 area hazard analysis work form title mps pps electronics shop location bldg & rm building 131 room 207 instructions an area hazard analysis aha is a process that is used to evaluate a work area to 1 determine the hazards that may be present 2 determine appropriate controls for these hazards and 3 provide a mechanism to communicate these hazards to someone entering the area the aha covers the facility and equipment within the facility it does not cover specific jobs tasks that may be performed in the area job task specific hazards and controls are covered by the jham process the aha should be done by the area manager in cooperation with the building manager an aha should be done once for all working areas and whenever there is a change to the facility or regulations or the introduction of new equipment or a new hazard enter information into boxes which will expand to accommodate whatever length of text is entered once this aha is complete the area responsible person signs processes equipment in area hazards recommended controls & actions work with lead soldering lead poisoning burn from soldering fume inhalation wear eye protection soldering receive lead safety training wash hands when tasks are complete use proper ventilation dispose of waste properly use of chemicals flux alcohol acetone cutting fluids and lubricants fire hazard eye and skin injury assure proper container labeling wash hands after use use proper ventilation dispose of waste properly use of portable power tools cuts and lacerations from flying material electric shock wear protective eyewear use double insulated tools if possible verify tools are in good repair use tools only according to manufacturers instructions use gfci with power tools page 2 use of hand tools cuts and lacerations from flying material wear protective eyewear verify tools are in good repair use the correct tool for the job electronic test equipment including the following dvms oscilloscopes power supplies electrical shocks and skin burns due to inappropriate use of electrical and electronic tools setup testing with the power off verify probes and test leads are in good repair evaluate the equipment to be tested if 50 5ma and 10 joules complete a non routine jham compressed air eye injury air injected into the skin wear safety glasses when working with compressed air use only approved and ported air nozzles working surfaces and aisle ways trip and slip hazards keep working surfaces uncluttered cleanup working area after each task is complete keep aisle ways clear of clutter store unused equipment when finished door to remain unlocked when occupied general working area egress know the location of exits fire extinguishers and safety equipment such as eye washes door to remain unlocked when occupied page 3 completed by print name date area responsible piero pianetta 8 1 08
